BERT – Pre-training of Deep Bidirectional Transformers for Language Understanding
Detailed Interview-Level Notes (Paragraph Format)
1. Introduction to BERT

BERT (Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers) is a pre-trained language representation model designed to learn deep bidirectional contextual representations from large-scale unlabeled text. It was introduced by researchers at Google and fundamentally changed the paradigm of natural language processing by demonstrating that pre-training a large language model and then fine-tuning it for specific tasks leads to state-of-the-art performance across many NLP benchmarks.

Prior language representation models typically relied on unidirectional context, meaning they processed text either from left-to-right or right-to-left. This limitation prevented the model from fully utilizing context from both sides simultaneously. BERT overcomes this issue by using a deep bidirectional Transformer encoder, enabling each token in the sequence to attend to both its preceding and succeeding tokens during training. This bidirectional representation allows BERT to capture richer linguistic patterns, syntactic relationships, and semantic dependencies.

The key innovation of BERT is its pre-training strategy, which combines two training objectives: Masked Language Modeling (MLM) and Next Sentence Prediction (NSP). After pre-training on massive corpora, the model can be fine-tuned with minimal architecture modifications for a wide variety of tasks such as question answering, sentiment analysis, natural language inference, and named entity recognition.

2. Background and Motivation

Before BERT, language representation models generally followed two approaches: feature-based approaches and fine-tuning approaches.

Feature-based models, such as ELMo, generate contextual embeddings that are used as input features for task-specific architectures. Although ELMo introduced contextual embeddings, it relied on separate left-to-right and right-to-left LSTM networks whose outputs were concatenated. As a result, it did not achieve deep bidirectional interaction between tokens.

Fine-tuning approaches, such as OpenAI GPT, use a pre-trained model that is later fine-tuned for downstream tasks. GPT is based on a left-to-right Transformer decoder, which means that during training each token can only attend to previous tokens. This restricts the model’s ability to incorporate future context.

BERT was designed to address these limitations by enabling deep bidirectional conditioning across all layers of the network. Instead of concatenating directional representations or restricting attention direction, BERT trains a Transformer encoder that allows tokens to attend to both left and right context simultaneously.

3. BERT Model Architecture

BERT is built on the Transformer encoder architecture introduced in the paper Attention Is All You Need by Ashish Vaswani and colleagues. The Transformer architecture relies on multi-head self-attention mechanisms, which enable the model to compute contextual representations by allowing each token to attend to every other token in the sequence.

BERT is available in two main configurations:

BERTBASE

12 Transformer layers

Hidden size of 768

12 attention heads

Approximately 110 million parameters

BERTLARGE

24 Transformer layers

Hidden size of 1024

16 attention heads

Approximately 340 million parameters

The model uses WordPiece tokenization with a vocabulary of around 30,000 tokens. WordPiece splits rare words into subword units, enabling the model to handle unknown words effectively.

Each input token representation in BERT is the sum of three embeddings:

Token embeddings – represent individual tokens in the vocabulary.

Segment embeddings – distinguish between sentences in sentence pair tasks.

Positional embeddings – encode token positions within the sequence.

Additionally, BERT introduces two special tokens:

[CLS] – inserted at the beginning of the sequence and used for classification tasks.

[SEP] – used to separate sentences in sentence-pair inputs.

4. Pre-training Tasks

BERT’s training relies on two unsupervised tasks designed to teach the model deep contextual understanding.

Masked Language Model (MLM)

The Masked Language Model objective allows BERT to learn bidirectional context by masking a subset of tokens in the input sequence and training the model to predict them. Specifically, 15% of tokens are randomly selected for prediction. Among these selected tokens:

80% are replaced with the [MASK] token.

10% are replaced with a random token.

10% remain unchanged.

This mixed masking strategy prevents the model from becoming overly dependent on the [MASK] token and reduces the discrepancy between pre-training and fine-tuning, since the [MASK] token does not appear during downstream tasks.

MLM enables the model to learn contextual relationships by using both left and right context when predicting masked tokens.

Next Sentence Prediction (NSP)

The Next Sentence Prediction task helps the model learn relationships between sentences. During training, the model receives pairs of sentences and must predict whether the second sentence logically follows the first in the original text.

The training data consists of:

50% positive examples (sentence B follows sentence A)

50% negative examples (sentence B is randomly sampled)

This objective is particularly useful for tasks that require understanding sentence relationships, such as:

Question answering

Natural language inference

Dialogue systems

5. Pre-training Data and Training Process

BERT is pre-trained on two large text corpora:

BooksCorpus (approximately 800 million words)

English Wikipedia (approximately 2.5 billion words)

These datasets provide diverse linguistic structures and long-form text that help the model learn contextual representations effectively.

Training is performed with the following configuration:

Batch size: 256 sequences

Maximum sequence length: 512 tokens

Total training steps: approximately 1 million

Optimizer: Adam with learning rate warmup and linear decay

Training large models such as BERTLARGE requires significant computational resources and was performed on Cloud TPUs, taking around four days.

6. Fine-Tuning for Downstream Tasks

One of the most important design principles of BERT is that the same architecture can be used for many different tasks with minimal modifications. Fine-tuning involves adding a small task-specific layer on top of the pre-trained model and training the entire model jointly.

For classification tasks such as sentiment analysis or natural language inference, the final hidden representation of the [CLS] token is passed to a softmax classifier.

For token-level tasks, such as Named Entity Recognition (NER), each token representation from the final layer is used to make predictions.

For question answering tasks like SQuAD, BERT predicts the start and end positions of the answer span within the passage.

Fine-tuning typically requires only a few epochs and significantly less data compared to training models from scratch.

7. Empirical Performance

BERT achieved state-of-the-art results on many benchmark datasets.

GLUE Benchmark

The General Language Understanding Evaluation (GLUE) benchmark consists of multiple tasks such as sentiment analysis, textual entailment, and paraphrase detection. BERTLARGE achieved an average GLUE score of 80.5, outperforming prior models by a large margin.

Question Answering

On the SQuAD v1.1 dataset, BERTLARGE achieved an F1 score of 93.2, surpassing human-level performance at the time.

For SQuAD v2.0, which includes unanswerable questions, BERT introduced a mechanism where predicting the [CLS] token indicates that no answer exists in the passage.

Commonsense Reasoning

On the SWAG dataset, which evaluates commonsense reasoning for sentence completion, BERTLARGE achieved 86.6% accuracy, significantly outperforming previous baselines.

8. Ablation Studies and Insights

Several experiments were conducted to analyze the contributions of different components.

Removing the Next Sentence Prediction task significantly degraded performance on sentence-level tasks such as MNLI and QNLI. This indicates that NSP helps the model learn relationships between sentences.

Experiments also showed that Masked Language Modeling outperforms traditional left-to-right language modeling, demonstrating the effectiveness of bidirectional context.

Another key finding is the impact of model scaling. Larger models consistently achieved better performance across all tasks. BERTLARGE, with 340 million parameters, outperformed BERTBASE even on smaller datasets.

The study also compared feature-based usage versus fine-tuning. While feature-based approaches achieved competitive results, fine-tuning consistently produced slightly better performance.

9. Real-World Applications

BERT has been widely adopted in many real-world NLP systems. Its ability to generate deep contextual embeddings makes it suitable for numerous applications.

In question answering systems, BERT can accurately locate answer spans within passages. In natural language inference, it can determine logical relationships between sentence pairs. For named entity recognition, BERT provides token-level contextual representations that improve entity classification accuracy.

Furthermore, BERT has influenced many subsequent models and architectures used in production systems for search engines, chatbots, document classification, and conversational AI.

10. Impact of BERT on NLP

BERT fundamentally changed the landscape of NLP by demonstrating the effectiveness of large-scale pre-training followed by task-specific fine-tuning. It showed that a single architecture could achieve state-of-the-art results across a wide variety of language understanding tasks.

The success of BERT also highlighted the importance of bidirectional context modeling, large-scale training data, and deep Transformer architectures. These insights have inspired many subsequent models such as RoBERTa, ALBERT, and DistilBERT.

Overall, BERT established transfer learning as the dominant paradigm in modern NLP, laying the foundation for the development of large language models and transformer-based architectures that power many AI systems today.
